# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-cordoba
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The earliest experimental AM transmissions began in the early 1900s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, widespread AM broadcasting was not established until the 1920s, following the development of vacuum tube receivers and transmitters.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] AM radio remained the dominant method of broadcasting for the next 30 years, a period called the "Golden Age of Radio", until television broadcasting became widespread in the 1950s and received much of the programming previously carried by radio.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Later, AM radio's audiences declined greatly due to competition from FM radio, digital radio, satellite radio, Internet radio, music streaming services, and podcasting.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Thus, AM broadcasters tend to specialize in spoken-word formats, such as talk radio, all-news radio and sports radio, with music formats primarily for FM and digital stations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] — Red Barber, *The Broadcasters*, 1970, pp.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In October 1898, a London publication, *The Electrician*, noted that "there are rare cases where, as Dr. [Oliver] Lodge once expressed it, it might be advantageous to 'shout' the message, spreading it broadcast to receivers in all directions".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, it was recognized that this would involve significant financial issues, as that same year *The Electrician* also commented "did not Prof.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] On January 1, 1902, Nathan Stubblefield gave a short-range "wireless telephone" demonstration, that included simultaneously broadcasting speech and music to seven locations throughout Murray, Kentucky.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The earliest public radiotelegraph broadcasts were provided as government services, beginning with daily time signals inaugurated on January 1, 1905, by a number of U.S.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In Europe, signals transmitted from a station located on the Eiffel Tower were received throughout much of Europe.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In both the United States and France this led to a small market of receiver lines geared for jewelers who needed accurate time to set their clocks, including the Ondophone in France, and the De Forest RS-100 Jewelers Time Receiver in the United States.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The ability to pick up time signal broadcasts, in addition to Morse code weather reports and news summaries, also attracted the interest of amateur radio enthusiasts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] It was immediately recognized that, much like the telegraph had preceded the invention of the telephone, the ability to make audio radio transmissions would be a significant technical advance.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Despite this knowledge, it still took two decades to perfect the technology needed to make quality audio transmissions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In addition, the telephone had rarely been used for distributing entertainment, outside of a few "telephone newspaper" systems, most of which were established in Europe, beginning with the Paris Théâtrophone.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] With this in mind, most early radiotelephone development envisioned that the device would be more profitably developed as a "wireless telephone" for personal communication, or for providing links where regular telephone lines could not be run, rather than for the uncertain finances of broadcasting.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The person generally credited as the primary early developer of AM technology is Canadian-born inventor Reginald Fessenden.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The original spark-gap radio transmitters were impractical for transmitting audio, since they produced discontinuous pulses known as "damped waves".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Fessenden realized that what was needed was a new type of radio transmitter that produced steady "undamped" (better known as "continuous wave") signals, which could then be "modulated" to reflect the sounds being transmitted.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Fessenden's basic approach was disclosed in U.S.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Patent 706,737, which he applied for on May 29, 1901, and was issued the next year.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] It called for the use of a high-speed alternator (referred to as "an alternating-current dynamo") that generated "pure sine waves" and produced "a continuous train of radiant waves of substantially uniform strength", or, in modern terminology, a continuous-wave (CW) transmitter.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Fessenden began his research on audio transmissions while doing developmental work for the United States Weather Service on Cobb Island, Maryland.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Because he did not yet have a continuous-wave transmitter, initially he worked with an experimental "high-frequency spark" transmitter, taking advantage of the fact that the higher the spark rate, the closer a spark-gap transmission comes to producing continuous waves.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] He later reported that, in the fall of 1900, he successfully transmitted speech over a distance of about 1.6 kilometers (one mile), which appears to have been the first successful audio transmission using radio signals.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, at this time the sound was far too distorted to be commercially practical.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] For a time he continued working with more sophisticated high-frequency spark transmitters, including versions that used compressed air, which began to take on some of the characteristics of arc-transmitters.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Fessenden attempted to sell this form of radiotelephone for point-to-point communication, but was unsuccessful.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Fessenden's work with high-frequency spark transmissions was only a temporary measure.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The next step, adopted from standard wire-telephone practice, was to insert a simple carbon microphone into the transmission line, to modulate the carrier wave signal to produce AM audio transmissions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, it would take many years of expensive development before even a prototype alternator-transmitter would be ready, and a few years beyond that for high-power versions to become available.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Fessenden worked with General Electric's (GE) Ernst F.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Alexanderson, who in August 1906, delivered an improved model which operated at a transmitting frequency of approximately 50 kHz, although at low power.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The alternator-transmitter achieved the goal of transmitting quality audio signals, but the lack of any way to amplify the signals meant they were somewhat weak.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] On December 21, 1906, Fessenden made an extensive demonstration of the new alternator-transmitter at Brant Rock, Massachusetts, showing its utility for point-to-point wireless telephony, including interconnecting his stations to the wire telephone network.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] As part of the demonstration, speech was transmitted 18 kilometers (11 miles) to a listening site at Plymouth, Massachusetts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Because there was no way to amplify electrical currents at this time, modulation was usually accomplished by a carbon microphone inserted directly in the antenna wire.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] This meant that the full transmitter power flowed through the microphone, and even using water cooling, the power handling ability of the microphones severely limited the power of the transmissions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Ultimately only a small number of large and powerful Alexanderson alternators would be developed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, they would be almost exclusively used for long-range radiotelegraph communication, and occasionally for radiotelephone experimentation, but were never used for general broadcasting.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Almost all of the continuous wave AM transmissions made prior to 1915 were made by versions of the arc converter transmitter, which had been initially developed by Valdemar Poulsen in 1903.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Arc transmitters worked by producing a pulsating electrical arc in an enclosed hydrogen atmosphere.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] They were much more compact than alternator transmitters, and could operate on somewhat higher transmitting frequencies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, they suffered from some of the same deficiencies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The lack of any means to amplify electrical currents meant that, like the alternator transmitters, modulation was usually accomplished by a microphone inserted directly in the antenna wire, which again resulted in overheating issues, even with the use of water-cooled microphones.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Thus, transmitter powers tended to be limited.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The arc was also somewhat unstable, which reduced audio quality.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Experimenters who used arc transmitters for their radiotelephone research included Ernst Ruhmer, Quirino Majorana, Charles "Doc" Herrold, and Lee de Forest.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Advances in vacuum tube technology (called "valves" in British usage), especially after around 1915, revolutionized radio technology.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Vacuum tube devices could be used to amplify electrical currents, which overcame the overheating issues of needing to insert microphones directly in the transmission antenna circuit.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Vacuum tube transmitters also provided high-quality AM signals, and could operate on higher transmitting frequencies than alternator and arc transmitters.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Vacuum tubes remained the central technology of radio for 40 years, until transistors began to dominate in the late 1950s, and are still used in the highest power broadcast transmitters.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Unlike telegraph and telephone systems, which used completely different types of equipment, most radio receivers were equally suitable for both radiotelegraph and radiotelephone reception.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 1903 and 1904, the electrolytic detector and thermionic diode (Fleming valve) were invented by Reginald Fessenden and John Ambrose Fleming, respectively.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Most important, in 1904–1906, the crystal detector, the simplest and cheapest AM detector, was developed by G.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Homemade crystal radios spread rapidly during the next 15 years, providing ready audiences for the first radio broadcasts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] One limitation of crystals sets was the lack of amplifying the signals, so listeners had to use earphones, and it required the development of vacuum-tube receivers before loudspeakers could be used.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The dynamic cone loudspeaker, invented in 1924, greatly improved audio frequency response over the previous horn speakers, allowing music to be reproduced with good fidelity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] AM radio offered the highest sound quality available in a home audio device prior to the introduction of the high-fidelity, long-playing record in the late 1940s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Listening habits changed in the 1960s due to the introduction of the revolutionary transistor radio (Regency TR-1, the first transistor radio released December 1954), which was made possible by the invention of the transistor in 1948.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] (The transistor was invented at Bell labs and released in June 1948.) Their compact size — small enough to fit in a shirt pocket — and lower power requirements, compared to vacuum tubes, meant that for the first time radio receivers were readily portable.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The transistor radio became the most widely used communication device in history, with billions manufactured by the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Radio became a ubiquitous "companion medium" which people could take with them anywhere they went.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The demarcation between what is considered "experimental" and "organized" broadcasting is largely arbitrary.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Following World War I, the number of stations providing a regular broadcasting service greatly increased, primarily due to advances in vacuum-tube technology.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, there were numerous cases of entertainment broadcasts being presented on a regular schedule before their formal recognition by government regulators.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Because most longwave radio frequencies were used for international radiotelegraph communication, a majority of early broadcasting stations operated on mediumwave frequencies, whose limited range generally restricted them to local audiences.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] One method for overcoming this limitation, as well as a method for sharing program costs, was to create radio networks, linking stations together with telephone lines to provide a nationwide audience.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In the U.S., the American Telephone and Telegraph Company (AT&T) was the first organization to create a radio network, and also to promote commercial advertising, which it called "toll" broadcasting.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Its flagship station, WEAF (now WFAN) in New York City, sold blocks of airtime to commercial sponsors that developed entertainment shows containing commercial messages.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] AT&T held a monopoly on quality telephone lines, and by 1924 had linked 12 stations in Eastern cities into a "chain".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The Radio Corporation of America (RCA), General Electric, and Westinghouse organized a competing network around its own flagship station, RCA's WJZ (now WABC) in New York City, but were hampered by AT&T's refusal to lease connecting lines or allow them to sell airtime.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 1926, AT&T sold its radio operations to RCA, which used them to form the nucleus of the new NBC network.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] By the 1930s, most of the major radio stations in the country were affiliated with networks owned by two companies, NBC and CBS.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 1934, a third national network, the Mutual Radio Network, was formed as a cooperative owned by its stations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] A second country which quickly adopted network programming was the United Kingdom, and its national network quickly became a prototype for a state-managed monopoly of broadcasting.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] A rising interest in radio broadcasting by the British public pressured the government to reintroduce the service, following its suspension in 1920.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, the government also wanted to avoid what it termed the "chaotic" U.S. experience of allowing large numbers of stations to operate with few restrictions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] There were also concerns about broadcasting becoming dominated by the Marconi company.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Arrangements were made for six large radio manufacturers to form a consortium, the British Broadcasting Company (BBC), established on October 18, 1922, which was given a monopoly on broadcasting.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] This enterprise was supported by a tax on radio sets sales, plus an annual license fee on receivers, collected by the Post Office.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Initially the eight stations were allowed regional autonomy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 1927, the original broadcasting organization was replaced by a government chartered British Broadcasting Corporation. an independent nonprofit supported solely by a 10 shilling receiver license fee.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Both highbrow and mass-appeal programs were carried by the National and Regional networks.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The period from the early 1920s through the 1940s is often called the "Golden Age of Radio".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] During this period AM radio was the main source of home entertainment, until it was replaced by television.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] For the first time entertainment was provided from outside the home, replacing traditional forms of entertainment such as oral storytelling and music from family members.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] New forms were created, including radio plays, mystery serials, soap operas, quiz shows, variety hours, situation comedies and children's shows.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Radio news, including remote reporting, allowed listeners to be vicariously present at notable events.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Radio greatly eased the isolation of rural life.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Political officials could now speak directly to millions of citizens.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] One of the first to take advantage of this was American president Franklin Roosevelt, who became famous for his fireside chats during the Great Depression.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, broadcasting also provided the means to use propaganda as a powerful government tool, and contributed to the rise of fascist and communist ideologies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In the 1940s, two new broadcast media, FM radio and television, began to provide extensive competition with the established broadcasting services.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The AM radio industry suffered a serious loss of audience and advertising revenue, and coped by developing new strategies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Instead of live music, most stations began playing less expensive recorded music.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In the late 1960s and 1970s, top 40 rock and roll stations in the U.S. and Canada such as WABC and CHUM transmitted highly processed and extended audio to 11 kHz, successfully attracting huge audiences.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In the late 1970s, spurred by the exodus of musical programming to FM stations, the AM radio industry in the United States developed technology for broadcasting in stereo.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Other nations adopted AM stereo, most commonly choosing Motorola's C-QUAM, and in 1993, the United States also made the C-QUAM system its standard, after a period allowing four different standards to compete.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The selection of a single standard improved acceptance of AM stereo, however overall there was limited adoption of AM stereo worldwide, and interest declined after 1990.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] With the continued migration of AM stations away from music to news, sports, and talk formats, receiver manufacturers saw little reason to adopt the more expensive stereo tuners, and thus radio stations have little incentive to upgrade to stereo transmission.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] This sometimes results in the sale of the transmitter site, with the station relocating to a more distant shared site using significantly less power, or completely shutting down operations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The ongoing development of alternative transmission systems, including DAB, satellite radio, and HD radio, continued the decline of the popularity of the traditional broadcast technologies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] These new options, including the introduction of Internet streaming, particularly resulted in the reduction of shortwave transmissions, as international broadcasters found ways to reach their audiences more easily.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However the United States Congress has introduced a bill to require all vehicles sold in the US to have an AM receiver to receive emergency broadcasts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The FM broadcast band was established in 1941 in the United States, and at the time some suggested that the AM band would soon be eliminated.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 1948, wide-band FM's inventor, Edwin H.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Since then the AM band's share of the audience has continued to decline.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 1987, the elimination of the Fairness Doctrine requirement meant that talk shows, which were commonly carried by AM stations, could adopt a more focused presentation on controversial topics, without the distraction of having to provide airtime for any contrasting opinions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In addition, satellite distribution made it possible for programs to be economically carried on a national scale.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The introduction of nationwide talk shows, most prominently Rush Limbaugh's beginning in 1988, was sometimes credited with "saving" AM radio.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, these stations tended to attract older listeners who were of lesser interest to advertisers, and AM radio's audience share continued to erode.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 1961, the FCC adopted a single standard for FM stereo transmissions, which was widely credited with enhancing FM's popularity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Developing the technology for AM broadcasting in stereo was challenging due to the need to limit the transmissions to a 20 kHz bandwidth, while also making the transmissions backward compatible with existing non-stereo receivers.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 1990, the FCC authorized an AM stereo standard developed by Magnavox, but two years later revised its decision to instead approve four competing implementations, saying it would "let the marketplace decide" which was best.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The lack of a common standard resulted in consumer confusion and increased the complexity and cost of producing AM stereo receivers.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 1993, the FCC again revised its policy, by selecting C-QUAM as the sole AM stereo implementation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] On June 8, 1988, an International Telecommunication Union (ITU)-sponsored conference held at Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, adopted provisions, effective July 1, 1990, to extend the upper end of the Region 2 AM broadcast band, by adding ten frequencies which spanned from 1610 kHz to 1700 kHz.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] At this time it was suggested that as many as 500 U.S. stations could be assigned to the new frequencies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] On April 12, 1990, the FCC voted to begin the process of populating the expanded band, with the main priority being the reduction of interference on the existing AM band, by transferring selected stations to the new frequencies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] It was now estimated that the expanded band could accommodate around 300 U.S. stations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, it turned out that the number of possible station reassignments was much lower, with a 2006 accounting reporting that, out of 4,758 licensed U.S.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] AM stations, only 56 were now operating on the expanded band.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] HD Radio is a digital audio broadcasting method developed by iBiquity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 2007, nighttime operation was also authorized.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The number of hybrid mode AM stations is not exactly known, because the FCC does not keep track of the stations employing the system, and some authorized stations have later turned it off.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] But as of 2020, the commission estimated that fewer than 250 AM stations were transmitting hybrid mode signals.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Despite the various actions, AM band audiences continued to contract, and the number of stations began to slowly decline.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] A 2009 FCC review reported that "The story of AM radio over the last 50 years has been a transition from being the dominant form of audio entertainment for all age groups to being almost non-existent to the youngest demographic groups.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Among persons aged 12–24, AM accounts for only 4% of listening, while FM accounts for 96%.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Among persons aged 25–34, AM accounts for only 9% of listening, while FM accounts for 91%.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 2009, the FCC made a major regulatory change, when it adopted a policy allowing AM stations to simulcast over FM translator stations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Translators had previously been available only to FM broadcasters, in order to increase coverage in fringe areas.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Their assignment for use by AM stations was intended to approximate the station's daytime coverage, which in cases where the stations reduced power at night, often resulted in expanded nighttime coverage.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Although the translator stations are not permitted to originate programming when the "primary" AM station is broadcasting, they are permitted to do so during nighttime hours for AM stations licensed for daytime-only operation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Prior to the adoption of the new policy, as of March 18, 2009, the FCC had issued 215 Special Temporary Authority grants for FM translators relaying AM stations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] After creation of the new policy, by 2011, there were approximately 500 in operation, and as of 2020, approximately 2,800 of the 4,570 licensed AM stations were rebroadcasting on one or more FM translators.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 2009, the FCC stated that "We do not intend to allow these cross-service translators to be used as surrogates for FM stations".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, based on station slogans, especially in the case of recently adopted musical formats, in most cases the expectation is that listeners will primarily be tuning into the FM signal rather than the nominally "primary" AM station.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] A 2020 review noted that "for many owners, keeping their AM stations on the air now is pretty much just about retaining their FM translator footprint rather than keeping the AM on the air on its own merits".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In 2018, the FCC, led by then-Commission Chairman Ajit Pai, proposed greatly reducing signal protection for 50 kW Class A "clear channel" stations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] This would allow co-channel secondary stations to operate with higher powers, especially at night.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] However, the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) expressed concerns that this would reduce the effectiveness of emergency communications.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] In May 2023, a bipartisan group of lawmakers in the United States introduced legislation making it illegal for automakers to eliminate AM radio from their cars.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The lawmakers argue that AM radio is an important tool for public safety due to being a component of the Emergency Alert System (EAS).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] Some automakers have been eliminating AM radio from their electric vehicles (EVs) due to interference from the electric motors, but the lawmakers argue that this is a safety risk and that car owners should have access to AM radio regardless of the type of vehicle they drive.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] The proposed legislation would require all new vehicles to include AM radio at no additional charge, and it would also require automakers that have already eliminated AM radio to inform customers of alternatives.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p01] DRM30 is another standard to broadcast on the AM bands, with implementation in India and China, among other countries.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] AM radio technology is simpler than later transmission systems.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] An AM receiver detects amplitude variations in the radio waves at a particular frequency, then amplifies changes in the signal voltage to operate a loudspeaker or earphone.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] In large urban centers, AM radio signals can be severely disrupted by metal structures and tall buildings.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] As a result, AM radio tends to do best in areas where FM frequencies are in short supply, or in thinly populated or mountainous areas where FM coverage is poor.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Great care must be taken to avoid mutual interference between stations operating on the same frequency.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] In general, an AM transmission needs to be about 20 times stronger than an interfering signal to avoid a reduction in quality, in contrast to FM signals, where the "capture effect" means that the dominant signal needs to only be about twice as strong as the interfering one.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] To allow room for more stations on the mediumwave broadcast band in the United States, in June 1989, the FCC adopted a National Radio Systems Committee (NRSC) standard that limited maximum transmitted audio bandwidth to 10.2 kHz, limiting occupied bandwidth to 20.4 kHz.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] The former audio limitation was 15 kHz resulting in bandwidth of 30 kHz.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Another common limitation on AM fidelity is the result of receiver design, although some efforts have been made to improve this, notably through the AMAX standards adopted in the United States.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] AM broadcasts are used on several frequency bands.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] The allocation of these bands is governed by the ITU's Radio Regulations and, on the national level, by each country's telecommunications administration (the FCC in the U.S., for example) subject to international agreements.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] The frequency ranges given here are those that are allocated to stations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Because of the bandwidth taken up by the sidebands, the range allocated for the band as a whole is usually about 5 kHz wider on either side.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Most of the earliest broadcasting experiments took place on longwave frequencies; however, complaints about interference from existing services, particularly the military, led to most broadcasting moving to higher frequencies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Most broadcast services use AM transmissions, although some use a modified version of AM such as Single-sideband modulation (SSB) or an AM-compatible version of SSB such as "SSB with carrier reinserted".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Beginning in the mid-1930s, the United States evaluated options for the establishment of broadcasting stations using much higher transmitting frequencies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] In October 1937, the FCC announced a second band of AM stations, consisting of 75 channels spanning from 41.02 to 43.98 MHz, which were informally called *Apex*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] The 40 kHz spacing between adjacent frequencies was four times that of the 10 kHz spacing used on the standard AM broadcast band, which reduced adjacent-frequency interference, and provided more bandwidth for high-fidelity programming.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] However, this band was eliminated effective on January 1, 1941, after the FCC determined that establishing a band of FM stations was preferable.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Beginning in the mid-1930s, starting with "The Brown Network" at Brown University in Providence, Rhode Island, a very low power broadcasting method known as carrier current was developed, and mostly adopted on U.S. college campuses.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] In this approach AM broadcast signals are distributed over electric power lines, which radiate a signal receivable at a short distance from the lines.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] In Switzerland a system known as "wire broadcasting" (*Telefonrundspruch* in German) transmitted AM signals over telephone lines in the longwave band until 1998, when it was shut down.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] In the UK, Rediffusion was an early pioneer of AM radio cable distribution.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Hybrid digital broadcast systems, which combine (mono analog) AM transmission with digital sidebands, have started to be used around the world.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] In the United States, iBiquity's proprietary HD Radio has been adopted and approved by the FCC for medium wave transmissions, while Digital Radio Mondiale is a more open effort often used on the shortwave bands, and can be used alongside many AM broadcasts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Both of these standards are capable of broadcasting audio of significantly greater fidelity than that of standard AM with current bandwidth limitations, and a theoretical frequency response of 0–16 kHz, in addition to stereo sound and text data.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Some microbroadcasters, especially those in the United States operating under the FCC's Part 15 rules, and pirate radio operators on mediumwave and shortwave, achieve greater range than possible on the FM band.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] On mediumwave these stations often transmit on 1610 kHz to 1710 kHz.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/am-broadcasting-p02] Microbroadcasting and pirate radio have generally been supplanted by streaming audio on the Internet, but some schools and hobbyists still use LPAM transmissions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] The **American Antiquarian Society** (**AAS**), located in Worcester, Massachusetts, is a learned society and a national research library of pre-twentieth-century American history and culture.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] Founded in 1812, it is the oldest historical society in the United States with a national focus.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] Its main building, known as Antiquarian Hall, is a U.S.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] National Historic Landmark in recognition of this legacy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] The mission of the AAS is to collect, preserve and make available for study all printed records of what is now known as the United States of America.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] This includes materials from the first European settlement through the year 1900.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] The collections of the AAS contain over four million books, pamphlets, newspapers, periodicals, graphic arts materials and manuscripts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] The Society is estimated to hold copies of two-thirds of the total books known to have been printed in what is now the United States from the establishment of the first press in 1640 through the year 1820; many of these volumes are exceedingly rare and a number of them are unique.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] Historic materials from all fifty U.S. states, most of Canada and the British West Indies are included in the AAS repository.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] An act of congress requires that one copy of the journals of the Senate and of the House of Representatives along with other documents are to be transmitted to the Governor of Massachusetts for the use and benefit of the Society.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] One of the more notable volumes held by the Society is a copy of the first book printed in America, the Bay Psalm Book.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] AAS has one of the largest collections of newspapers printed in America through 1876, with more than two million issues in its collection.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] On the initiative of Isaiah Thomas, the AAS was founded on October 24, 1812, through an act of the Massachusetts General Court.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] It was the third historical society established in America, and the first to be national in its scope.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] Isaiah Thomas started the collection with approximately 8,000 books from his personal library.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] The first library building was erected in 1820 in downtown Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] In 1853, the Society moved its collections to a larger building at the corner of Highland Street, also in Worcester.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] This building was later abandoned and another new building was constructed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] Designed by Winslow, Bigelow & Wadsworth, the Georgian Revival building was completed in 1910 and stands on the corner of Park Avenue and Salisbury Street.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] There have been several additions to this building to accommodate the growing collection.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] The most recent addition was completed in 2019 and created room for an updated HVAC system, conservation lab, and multi-use learning lab.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] AAS was presented with the 2013 National Humanities Medal by President Obama in a ceremony at the White House.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] As part of AAS's mission as a learned society, it offers a variety of public lectures and seminars.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] One topic to which AAS dedicates significant academic energies is printing technology, especially in 18th century British North America.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] Since Isaiah Thomas was a newspaper man himself, he collected a large number of printed materials.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] With regard to printing, paper making, edition setting, and reprinting, not much had changed in European technology by the eighteenth century.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] It was not until the late eighteenth century that paper-making material began to evolve from a hand-woven cloth to an industrial pulp.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] AAS undertakes special efforts to preserve printed records from this time period, as the Society maintains an on-site conservation department with various sewing, cloth, and binding materials to aid in the preservation process.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] Over its two-hundred-year history, the Society has had 14 formal leaders who have shaped the organization's vision, collections, and day-to-day operations.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] Leadership roles at the AAS have historically overlapped in chronology, as different roles oversaw different aspects of the Society simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/american-antiquarian-society] The American Antiquarian Society's membership includes scholars, writers, journalists, historians, artists, filmmakers, collectors, American presidents, and civic leaders.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] The **real** was the currency of Argentina until 1881.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] From 1822, it was subdivided into 10 *décimos*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] The sol was also issued during this period and was equal to the real, whilst the peso was worth 8 reales and the escudo was worth 16 reales.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] Spanish colonial reales circulated alone until 1813, when Argentina began issuing its own coins.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] In 1826, the peso moneda corriente and peso fuerte were introduced in paper money only.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] In 1854, coins were issued denominated in centavos.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] However, decimalization did not occur until in 1881, when the real was replaced by the peso moneda nacional at a rate of 8 reales to 1 peso.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] Silver coins were issued in the name of the "Río de la Plata Province" in denominations of 1⁄2, 1, 2, 4 and 8 reales and 1⁄2, 1, 2, 4 and 8 soles, whilst gold coins (87.5%) were issued in denomination of 1, 2, 4 and 8 escudos.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] The state of Buenos Aires issued its own coins starting in 1822, denominated in reales and *décimos*, with 10 décimos = 1 real.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] Coins were issued in denominations of 1, 5, 10 and 20 décimos, together with 1⁄4, 1⁄2 (actually shown as 5⁄10), 1 and 2 reales.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] Other provinces issued coins denominated in reales (silver) and escudos (gold): Córdoba, Entre Ríos, La Rioja, Mendoza, Salta, Santiago del Estero and Tucumán.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] Since these coins were scarce, it was common to use silver coins from other countries (especially Bolivian soles).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] In 1854, coins were issued in the name of the "Argentine Confederation" in denominations of 1, 2 and 4 centavo coins.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] As notes above, this issue did not lead to full decimalization.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] In 1820, the Government of the Province of Buenos Aires introduced notes in denominations of 5, 10, 20, 40, 50 and 100 pesos.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] These were followed in 1823 by 1, 3 and 5 pesos.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/argentine-real] The *Banco de Buenos Ayres* began issuing notes in 1822 in denominations of 20, 50, 100, 200, 500 and 1000 pesos.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The **Aztecs** (/ˈæztɛks/ *AZ-teks*) were a Mesoamerican civilization that flourished in central Mexico from 1300 to 1521.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Aztec people included different ethnic groups of central Mexico, particularly those groups who spoke the Nahuatl language.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Aztec culture was organized into city-states (*altepetl*), some of which joined to form alliances, political confederations, or empires.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Aztec Empire was a confederation of three city-states established in 1427: Tenochtitlan (the capital city of the Mexica or Tenochca), Tetzcoco, and Tlacopan, previously part of the Tepanec empire, whose dominant power was Azcapotzalco.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Although the term Aztecs is often narrowly restricted to the Mexica of Tenochtitlan, it is also broadly used to refer to Nahua polities or peoples of central Mexico in the pre-Hispanic era, as well as the Spanish colonial era (1521–1821).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Most ethnic groups of central Mexico in the post-classic period shared essential cultural traits of Mesoamerica.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The culture of central Mexico includes maize cultivation, the social division between nobility (*pipiltin*) and commoners (*macehualtin*), a pantheon, and the calendric system.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Particular to the Mexica of Tenochtitlan was the patron god Huitzilopochtli, twin pyramids, and the ceramic styles known as Aztec I to IV.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Mexica were late-comers to the Valley of Mexico, and founded the city-state of Tenochtitlan on unpromising islets in Lake Texcoco, later becoming the dominant power of the Aztec Triple Alliance or Aztec Empire which conquered other city-states throughout Mesoamerica.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] It originated in 1427 as an alliance between the city-states Tenochtitlan, Texcoco, and Tlacopan to defeat the Tepanec state of Azcapotzalco, which had previously dominated the Basin of Mexico.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Soon Texcoco and Tlacopan were relegated to junior partnership in the alliance, with Tenochtitlan the dominant power.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The empire extended its reach by a combination of trade and military conquest.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Client city-states paid taxes, not tribute to the Aztec emperor, the *Huey Tlatoani*, in an economic strategy limiting communication and trade between outlying polities, making them dependent on the imperial center for the acquisition of luxury goods.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The political clout of the empire reached far south into Mesoamerica conquering polities as far south as Chiapas and Guatemala and spanning Mesoamerica from the Pacific to the Atlantic oceans.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The empire reached its maximum extent in 1519, just before the arrival of Spanish conquistadors led by Hernán Cortés.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Cortés allied with city-states opposed to the Mexica, particularly the Nahuatl-speaking Tlaxcalteca as well as other central Mexican polities, including Texcoco, its former ally in the Triple Alliance.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] After the fall of Tenochtitlan on 13 August 1521 and the capture of the emperor Cuauhtémoc, the Spanish founded Mexico City on the ruins of Tenochtitlan and proceeded with the process of conquest and incorporation of Mesoamerican peoples into the Spanish Empire.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] With the destruction of the superstructure of the Aztec Empire in 1521, the Spanish used the city-states on which the Aztec Empire had been built to rule the indigenous populations via their local nobles.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Nobles acted as intermediaries to convey taxes and mobilize labor for their new overlords, facilitating the establishment of Spanish colonial rule.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Important for knowledge of post-conquest Nahuas was the training of indigenous scribes to write alphabetic texts in Nahuatl, mainly for local purposes under Spanish colonial rule.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] At its height, Aztec culture had rich and complex philosophical, mythological, and religious traditions, as well as remarkable architectural and artistic accomplishments.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Nahuatl words *aztēcatl* (Nahuatl pronunciation: [asˈteːkat͡ɬ], singular) and *aztēcah* (Nahuatl pronunciation: [asˈteːkaʔ], plural) mean "people from Aztlán", a mythical place of origin for several ethnic groups in central Mexico.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The term was not used as an endonym by the Aztecs themselves, but it is found in the different migration accounts of the Mexica, where it describes the different tribes who left Aztlan together.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In one account of the journey from Aztlan, Huitzilopochtli, the tutelary deity of the Mexica tribe, tells his followers on the journey that "now, no longer is your name Azteca, you are now Mexitin [Mexica]".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The usage of the term "Aztec" in describing the empire and its people has been criticized by Robert H.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Barlow, who preferred the term "**Culhua-Mexica**" in reference to the empire's people, and by Pedro Carrasco, who prefers the term "Tenochca Empire" in reference to their state.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Carrasco writes about the term "Aztec" that "it is of no use for understanding the ethnic complexity of ancient Mexico and for identifying the dominant element in the political entity we are studying".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In other contexts, Aztec may refer to all the various city-states and their peoples, who shared large parts of their ethnic history and cultural traits with the Mexica, Acolhua, and Tepanecs, and who often also used the Nahuatl language as a lingua franca.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Offner's *Law and Politics in Aztec Texcoco*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In this meaning, it is possible to talk about an "Aztec civilization" including all the particular cultural patterns common for most of the peoples inhabiting central Mexico in the late postclassic period.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Such usage may also extend the term "Aztec" to all the groups in Central Mexico that were incorporated culturally or politically into the sphere of dominance of the Aztec empire.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] When used to describe ethnic groups, the term "Aztec" refers to several Nahuatl-speaking peoples of central Mexico in the postclassic period of Mesoamerican chronology, especially the Mexica, the ethnic group that had a leading role in establishing the hegemonic empire based at Tenochtitlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The term extends to further ethnic groups associated with the Aztec empire, such as the Acolhua, the Tepanec, and others that were incorporated into the empire.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Charles Gibson enumerates many groups in central Mexico that he includes in his study *The Aztecs Under Spanish Rule* (1964).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] These include the Culhuaque, Cuitlahuaque, Mixquica, Xochimilca, Chalca, Tepaneca, Acolhuaque, and Mexica.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In older usage, the term was commonly used about modern Nahuatl-speaking ethnic groups, as Nahuatl was previously referred to as the "Aztec language".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In recent usage, these ethnic groups are referred to as the Nahua peoples.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Linguistically, the term "Aztecan" is still used about the branch of the Uto-Aztecan languages (also sometimes called the Uto-Nahuan languages) that includes the Nahuatl language and its closest relatives Pochutec and Pipil.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] To the Aztecs themselves the word "Aztec" was not an endonym for any particular ethnic group.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Rather, it was an umbrella term used to refer to several ethnic groups, not all of them Nahuatl-speaking, that claimed heritage from the mythic place of origin, Aztlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Alexander von Humboldt originated the modern usage of "Aztec" in 1810, as a collective term applied to all the people linked by trade, custom, religion, and language to the Mexica state and the Triple Alliance.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In 1843, with the publication of the work of William H.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Prescott on the history of the conquest of Mexico, the term was adopted by most of the world, including 19th-century Mexican scholars who saw it as a way to distinguish present-day Mexicans from pre-conquest Mexicans.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This usage has been the subject of debate in more recent years, but the term "Aztec" is still more common.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Knowledge of Aztec society rests on several different sources: The many archeological remains of everything from temple pyramids to thatched huts can be used to understand many of the aspects of what the Aztec world was like.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] However, archeologists often must rely on knowledge from other sources to interpret the historical context of artifacts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] There are many written texts by the indigenous people and Spaniards of the early colonial period that contain invaluable information about pre-colonial Aztec history.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] These texts provide insight into the political histories of various Aztec city-states, and their ruling lineages.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Such histories were produced as well in pictorial codices.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Some of these manuscripts were entirely pictorial, often with glyphs.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In the postconquest era, many other texts were written in Latin script by either literate Aztecs or by Spanish friars who interviewed the native people about their customs and stories.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] An important pictorial and alphabetic text produced in the early sixteenth century was *Codex Mendoza*, named after the first viceroy of Mexico and perhaps commissioned by him, to inform the Spanish crown about the political and economic structure of the Aztec empire.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] It has information naming the polities that the Triple Alliance conquered, the types of taxes rendered to the Aztec Empire, and the class/gender structure of their society.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Many written annals exist, written by local Nahua historians recording the histories of their polity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] These annals used pictorial histories and were subsequently transformed into alphabetic annals in Latin script.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Well-known native chroniclers and annalists are Chimalpahin of Amecameca-Chalco; Fernando Alvarado Tezozomoc of Tenochtitlan; Alva Ixtlilxochitl of Texcoco, Juan Bautista Pomar of Texcoco, and Diego Muñoz Camargo of Tlaxcala.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] There are also many accounts by Spanish conquerors who participated in the Spanish invasion, such as Bernal Díaz del Castillo who wrote a full history of the conquest.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Spanish friars also produced documentation in chronicles and other types of accounts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Of key importance is Toribio de Benavente Motolinia, one of the first twelve Franciscans arriving in Mexico in 1524.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Another Franciscan of great importance was Fray Juan de Torquemada, author of *Monarquia Indiana*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Dominican Diego Durán also wrote extensively about pre-Hispanic religion as well as the history of the Mexica.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] An invaluable source of information about many aspects of Aztec religious thought, political and social structure, as well as the history of the Spanish conquest from the Mexica viewpoint is the Florentine Codex.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Another source of knowledge is the cultures and customs of the contemporary Nahuatl speakers who can often provide insights into what pre-Hispanic ways of life may have been like.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Scholarly study of Aztec civilization is most often based on scientific and multidisciplinary methodologies, combining archeological knowledge with ethnohistorical and ethnographic information.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] It is a matter of debate whether the enormous city of Teotihuacan was inhabited by speakers of Nahuatl, or whether Nahuas had not yet arrived in central Mexico in the classic period.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] It is generally agreed that the Nahua peoples were not indigenous to the highlands of central Mexico, but that they gradually migrated into the region from somewhere in northwestern Mexico.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] At the fall of Teotihuacan in the 6th century CE, some city-states rose to power in central Mexico, some of them, including Cholula and Xochicalco, probably inhabited by Nahuatl speakers.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] One study has suggested that Nahuas originally inhabited the Bajío area around Guanajuato which reached a population peak in the 6th century, after which the population quickly diminished during a subsequent dry period.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This depopulation of the Bajío coincided with an incursion of new populations into the Valley of Mexico, which suggests that this marks the influx of Nahuatl speakers into the region.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] These people populated central Mexico, dislocating speakers of Oto-Manguean languages as they spread their political influence south.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] As the former nomadic hunter-gatherer peoples mixed with the complex civilizations of Mesoamerica, adopting religious and cultural practices, the foundation for later Aztec culture was laid.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] After 900 CE, during the postclassic period, many sites almost certainly inhabited by Nahuatl speakers became powerful.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Among them are the site of Tula, Hidalgo, and also city-states such as Tenayuca, and Colhuacan in the valley of Mexico and Cuauhnahuac in Morelos.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In the ethnohistorical sources from the colonial period, the Mexica themselves describe their arrival in the Valley of Mexico.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The ethnonym Aztec (Nahuatl *Aztecah*) means "people from Aztlan", Aztlan being a mythical place of origin toward the north.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Hence the term applied to all those peoples who claimed to carry the heritage from this mythical place.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The migration stories of the Mexica tribe tell how they traveled with other tribes, including the Tlaxcalteca, Tepaneca, and Acolhua, but that eventually their tribal deity Huitzilopochtli told them to split from the other Aztec tribes and take on the name "Mexica".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] At the time of their arrival, there were many Aztec city-states in the region.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The most powerful were Colhuacan to the south and Azcapotzalco to the west.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Tepanecs of Azcapotzalco soon expelled the Mexica from Chapultepec and executed the first Aztec royal family except Queen Chimalxochitl II.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In 1299, Colhuacan ruler Cocoxtli permitted them to settle in the empty barrens of Tizapan, where they were eventually assimilated into Culhuacan culture.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The noble lineage of Colhuacan traced its roots back to the legendary city-state of Tula, and by marrying into Colhua families, the Mexica now appropriated this heritage.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] After living in Colhuacan, the Mexica were again expelled and were forced to move.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] According to Aztec legend, in 1323, the Mexica were shown a vision of an eagle perched on a prickly pear cactus, eating a snake.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The vision indicated where they were to build their settlement.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Mexica founded Tenochtitlan on a small swampy island in Lake Texcoco, the inland lake of the Basin of Mexico.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The year of foundation is usually given as 1325.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In 1376 the Mexica royal dynasty was founded when Acamapichtli was elected as the first *Huey Tlatoani* of Tenochtitlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In the first 50 years after the founding of the Mexica dynasty, the Mexica were a tributary of Azcapotzalco, which had become a major regional power under the ruler Tezozomoc.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Mexica supplied the Tepaneca with warriors for their successful conquest campaigns in the region and received part of the tribute from the conquered city-states.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In this way, the political standing and economy of Tenochtitlan gradually grew.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In 1396, at Acamapichtli's death, his son Huitzilihhuitl (lit.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] "Hummingbird feather") became ruler; married to Tezozomoc's daughter, the relationship with Azcapotzalco remained close.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] "She smokes like a shield"), son of Huitzilihhuitl, became ruler of Tenochtitlan in 1417.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In 1418, Azcapotzalco initiated a war against the Acolhua of Texcoco and killed their ruler Ixtlilxochitl.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Even though Ixtlilxochitl was married to Chimalpopoca's daughter, the Mexica ruler continued to support Tezozomoc.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Tezozomoc died in 1426, and his sons began a struggle for the rulership of Azcapotzalco.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] During this power struggle, Chimalpopoca died, probably killed by Tezozomoc's son Maxtla who saw him as a competitor.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Itzcoatl, brother of Huitzilihhuitl and uncle of Chimalpopoca, was elected the next Mexica *tlatoani*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Mexica were now in open war with Azcapotzalco and Itzcoatl petitioned for an alliance with Nezahualcoyotl, son of the slain Texcocan ruler Ixtlilxochitl against Maxtla.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Itzcoatl also allied with Maxtla's brother Totoquihuaztli ruler of the Tepanec city of Tlacopan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Triple Alliance of Tenochtitlan, Texcoco, and Tlacopan besieged Azcapotzalco, and in 1428 they destroyed the city and sacrificed Maxtla.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Through this victory, Tenochtitlan became the dominant city-state in the Valley of Mexico, and the alliance between the three city-states provided the basis on which the Aztec Empire was built.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Itzcoatl proceeded by securing a power basis for Tenochtitlan, by conquering the city-states on the southern lake – including Culhuacan, Xochimilco, Cuitlahuac, and Mizquic.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] These states had an economy based on highly productive chinampa agriculture, cultivating human-made extensions of rich soil in the shallow lake Xochimilco.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Itzcoatl then undertook further conquests in the valley of Morelos, subjecting the city-state of Cuauhnahuac (today Cuernavaca).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In 1440, Moteuczomatzin Ilhuicamina (lit.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] "he frowns like a lord, he shoots the sky") was elected tlatoani; he was the son of Huitzilihhuitl, brother of Chimalpopoca and had served as the war leader of his uncle Itzcoatl in the war against the Tepanecs.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The accession of a new ruler in the dominant city-state was often an occasion for subjected cities to rebel by refusing to pay taxes.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This meant that new rulers began their rule with a coronation campaign, often against rebellious provinces, but also sometimes demonstrating their military might by making new conquests.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Motecuzoma tested the attitudes of the cities around the valley by requesting laborers for the enlargement of the Great Temple of Tenochtitlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Only the city of Chalco refused to provide laborers, and hostilities between Chalco and Tenochtitlan would persist until the 1450s.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] During this period the city-states of Tlaxcalan, Cholula and Huexotzinco emerged as major competitors to the imperial expansion, and they supplied warriors to several of the cities conquered.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Motecuzoma therefore initiated a state of low-intensity warfare against these three cities, staging minor skirmishes called "Flower Wars" (Nahuatl *xochiyaoyotl*) against them, perhaps as a strategy of exhaustion.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In the Valley of Oaxaca, which was invaded by Moctezuma's forces in the 1450s, the Aztec Empire would oppress the Mixtec and Zapotec peoples, who they would also require to pay tributes.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Motecuzoma I also consolidated the political structure of the Triple Alliance and the internal political organization of Tenochtitlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In 1469, the next ruler was Axayacatl (lit.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] "Water mask"), son of Itzcoatl's son Tezozomoc and Motecuzoma I's daughter Atotoztli II.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He undertook a successful coronation campaign far south of Tenochtitlan against the Zapotecs in the Isthmus of Tehuantepec.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Axayacatl also conquered the independent Mexica city of Tlatelolco, located on the northern part of the island where Tenochtitlan was also located.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Tlatelolco ruler Moquihuix was married to Axayacatl's sister, and his alleged mistreatment of her was used as an excuse to incorporate Tlatelolco and its important market directly under the control of the tlatoani of Tenochtitlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Axayacatl then conquered areas in Central Guerrero, the Puebla Valley, on the gulf coast and against the Otomi and Matlatzinca in the Toluca Valley.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Toluca Valley was a buffer zone against the powerful Tarascan state in Michoacan, against which Axayacatl turned next.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In the major campaign against the Tarascans (Nahuatl languages: *Michhuahqueh*) in 1478–1479 the Aztec forces were repelled by a well-organized defense.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Axayacatl was soundly defeated in a battle at Tlaximaloyan (today Tajimaroa), losing most of his 32,000 men and only barely escaping back to Tenochtitlan with the remnants of his army.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In 1481 at Axayacatls death, his older brother Tizoc was elected ruler.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Tizoc's coronation campaign against the Otomi of Metztitlan failed as he lost the major battle and only managed to secure 40 prisoners to be sacrificed for his coronation ceremony.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Having shown weakness, many cities rebelled and consequently, most of Tizoc's short reign was spent attempting to quell rebellions and maintain control of areas conquered by his predecessors.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Tizoc died suddenly in 1485, and it has been suggested that he was poisoned by his brother and war leader Ahuitzotl who became the next tlatoani.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Tizoc is mostly known as the namesake of the Stone of Tizoc a monumental sculpture (Nahuatl *temalacatl*), decorated with a representation of Tizoc's conquests.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] "Water monster"), brother of Axayacatl and Tizoc and war leader under Tizoc.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] His successful coronation campaign suppressed rebellions in the Toluca Valley and conquered Jilotepec and several communities in the northern Valley of Mexico.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] A second 1521 campaign to the gulf coast was also highly successful.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He began an enlargement of the Great Temple of Tenochtitlan, inaugurating the new temple in 1487.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] For the inauguration ceremony, the Mexica invited the rulers of all their subject cities, who participated as spectators in the ceremony in which an unprecedented number of war captives were sacrificed – some sources giving a figure of 80,400 prisoners sacrificed over four days.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Probably the actual figure of sacrifices was much smaller, but still numbering several thousand.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] There have never been found enough skulls in the capital to satisfy even the most conservative figures.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Ahuitzotl also constructed monumental architecture in sites such as Calixtlahuaca, Malinalco, and Tepoztlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] After a rebellion in the towns of Alahuiztlan and Oztoticpac in Northern Guerrero, he ordered the entire population executed and repopulated with people from the valley of Mexico.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He also constructed a fortified garrison at Oztuma defending the border against the Tarascan state.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Motecuhzoma Xocoyotzin is known to world history as the Aztec ruler when the Spanish invaders and their indigenous allies began their conquest of the empire in a two-year-long campaign (1519–1521).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] His early rule did not hint at his future fame.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He succeeded in the rulership after the death of Ahuitzotl.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] "He frowns like a lord, the youngest child who is dead as he had lived in life but not death"), was a son of Axayacatl, and a war leader.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He began his rule in standard fashion, conducting a coronation campaign to demonstrate his skills as a leader.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He attacked the fortified city of Nopallan in Oaxaca and subjected the adjacent region to the empire.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He also consolidated the class structure of Aztec society, by making it harder for commoners (Nahuatl languages: *macehualtin*) to accede to the privileged class of the *pipiltin* through merit in combat.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He also instituted a strict sumptuary code limiting the types of luxury goods that could be consumed by commoners.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In 1517, Moctezuma received the first news of ships with strange warriors having landed on the Gulf Coast near Cempoallan and he dispatched messengers to greet them and find out what was happening, and he ordered his subjects in the area to keep him informed of any new arrivals.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In 1519, he was informed of the arrival of the Spanish fleet of Hernán Cortés, who soon marched toward Tlaxcala where he allied with the traditional enemies of the Aztecs.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] On 8 November 1519, Moctezuma II received Cortés and his troops and Tlaxcalan allies on the causeway south of Tenochtitlan, and he invited the Spaniards to stay as his guests in Tenochtitlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] When Aztec troops destroyed a Spanish camp on the Gulf Coast, Cortés ordered Moctezuma to execute the commanders responsible for the attack, and Moctezuma complied.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] At this point, the power balance had shifted toward the Spaniards who now held Moctezuma as a prisoner in his palace.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] As this shift in power became clear to Moctezuma's subjects, the Spaniards became increasingly unwelcome in the capital city, and, in June 1520, hostilities broke out, culminating in the massacre in the Great Temple, and a major uprising of the Mexica against the Spanish.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] During the fighting, Moctezuma was killed, either by the Spaniards who killed him as they fled the city, or by the Mexica themselves who considered him a traitor.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Cuitláhuac, a kinsman and adviser to Moctezuma, succeeded him as tlatoani, mounting the defense of Tenochtitlan against the Spanish invaders and their indigenous allies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He ruled for only 80 days, perhaps dying in a smallpox epidemic, although early sources do not give the cause.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He was succeeded by Cuauhtémoc, the last independent Mexica tlatoani, who continued the fierce defense of Tenochtitlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Aztecs were weakened by disease, and the Spanish enlisted tens of thousands of Indian allies, especially Tlaxcalans, for the assault on Tenochtitlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] After the siege and destruction of the Aztec capital, Cuauhtémoc was captured on 13 August 1521, marking the beginning of Spanish hegemony in central Mexico.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Spaniards held Cuauhtémoc captive until he was tortured and executed on the orders of Cortés, supposedly for treason, during an ill-fated expedition to Honduras in 1525.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] His death marked the end of a tumultuous era in Aztec political history.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] After the fall of the Aztec Empire, entire Nahua communities were subject to forced labor under the *encomienda* system, the Aztec education system was abolished and replaced by a very limited church education, and Aztec religious practices were forcibly replaced with Catholicism.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Following the Spanish and their indigenous allies' victory over the Triple Alliance, its *tlatloque* – Cuauhtémoc, captured on 13 August 1521 – was not immediately deposed of his titular throne while in captivity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Rather, the Spanish maintained his nominal, but not actual authority, while they established a foothold in the Valley of Mexico, and understanding thereof.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This dynamic also was to avoid ceding control over the Valley to their allies, who neighbored and detested the former Triple Alliance for its historic bellicosity towards them and their peoples.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The account continues that Cortés accepted Cuauhtémoc's request to leave the Mexica unharmed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Cortés later recanted his obligations upon seeing that the war bounty collected from the conquest did not meet his expectations, and proceeded to torture Cuauhtémoc by forcing him to walk over hot coals, out of the belief that he had attempted to hide more valuables.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] These valuables would not be recovered to the extent desired by Cortés.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] There are, however, no Mexica sources describing these events, possibly due to the mass-destruction of indigenous texts during conquest.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Cuauhtémoc was the last *tlatoani* with full sovereign authority, as well as the last *tlatoque* whose title came through to him through dynastic lineage until the throne's dynastic restoration in 1538.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In the period immediately succeeding Cuauhtémoc's deposition, successors were directly installed by the Spanish to facilitate easier control of their new colony.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This practice was employed by the Spanish in numerous areas throughout the early stages of conquest.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This was to navigate the inherent difficulty in administer a foreign government in an incompletely understood land, whose people at the time were still recovering from war and plagued by European-introduced disease.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Additionally, a puppet government served as an attempt to create an image of legitimacy towards the indigenous Mesoamericans.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] These installed *tlatoani* were known as *Cuāuhtlahtoāni*, meaning "the one who speaks like eagle" in Náhuatl, and as appointments, did not undergo the traditional Mexica investiture ceremony pursued with normal *tlatoani*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This invalidated the *Cuahtlatoani*'s authority and right to rule in the eyes of their "subjects".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The *Cuauhtlatoani* were not a novel concept, but had precedent, as the term was used pre-conquest to describe an interim, non-dynastic regent with *tlatloque*-like authority.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Generally, *cuauhtlatoani* would be appointed by *tlatoani* to administer recently-conquered lands, such as the *Atlepetl* of Tlatelolco following the 1473 defeat of its last Tlatoani – Moquihuix – by the Triple Alliance.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Tlatelolco was governed by *cuauhtlatoque* until the death of Itzquauhtzin in 1520.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The term *cuauhtlatoani* is also sometimes used in early 16th-century codices to describe the mythic first leaders of the Mexica during their migration from Aztlán.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] There were three *cuauhtlatoani* of Tenochtitlan before the restoration of dynastically-derived rulership to the atlepetl in 1565.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] 1538 saw the dynastic rulership restored to the throne of Tenochtitlan, still in a dynamic of vassalage to the authority expressed by the conquistadors in the name of the Spanish crown.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The reasoning behind this choice is not certain, but it was probably made by the Spanish viceroy of New Spain from 1535 to 1550, Antonio de Mendoza, in pursuit of a more authoritative appearance of legitimacy in regards to Spanish rule over the Mexica.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The restoration entailed a revalidation of the role of Mexica nobility in the selection of a *tlatloque*, where a candidate they elected would be forwarded to the Spanish authority for confirmation and installation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This helped forward an air of authority and responsibility in the eye of the Mexica towards the Spanish and the new *tlatoani*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This period saw four tlatoani with one *cuauhtlatoque* acting to serve in only a transitional role between *tlatoani*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The reason for this interregnum and its significant length is, to date, unknown.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] These governorships would, at least initially, be held by indigenous or mestizo administrators, none of which, however, were dynastically contiguous with the *tlatloque*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The highest class was the *pīpiltin* or nobility.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The *pilli* status was hereditary and ascribed certain privileges to its holders, such as the right to wear particularly fine garments and consume luxury goods, as well as to own land and direct corvee labor by commoners.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The most powerful nobles were called lords (Nahuatl languages: *teuctin*) and they owned and controlled noble estates or houses, and could serve in the highest government positions or as military leaders.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Nobles made up about five percent of the population.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The second class was the *mācehualtin*, originally peasants, but later extended to the lower working classes in general.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Eduardo Noguera estimates that in later stages only 20 percent of the population was dedicated to agriculture and food production.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The other 80 percent of society were warriors, artisans, and traders.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Eventually, most of the *mācehuallis* were dedicated to arts and crafts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Their works were an important source of income for the city.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Macehualtin could become enslaved, (Nahuatl languages: *tlacotin*) for example if they had to sell themselves into the service of a noble due to debt or poverty, but enslavement was not an inherited status among the Aztecs.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Some macehualtin were landless and worked directly for a lord (Nahuatl languages: *mayehqueh*), whereas the majority of commoners were organized into calpollis which gave them access to land and property.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Commoners were able to obtain privileges similar to those of the nobles by demonstrating prowess in warfare.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] When a warrior took a captive he accrued the right to use certain emblems, weapons, or garments, and as he took more captives his rank and prestige increased.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Aztec family pattern was bilateral, counting relatives on the father's and mother's side of the family equally, and inheritance was also passed both to sons and daughters.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This meant that women could own property just as men and that women therefore had a good deal of economic freedom from their spouses.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Nevertheless, Aztec society was highly gendered with separate gender roles for men and women.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Men were expected to work outside of the house, as farmers, traders, craftsmen, and warriors, whereas women were expected to take responsibility for the domestic sphere.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Women could however also work outside of the home as small-scale merchants, doctors, priests, and midwives.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Warfare was highly valued and a source of high prestige, but women's work was metaphorically conceived of as equivalent to warfare, and as equally important in maintaining the equilibrium of the world and pleasing the gods.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] This situation has led some scholars to describe Aztec gender ideology as an ideology not of a gender hierarchy, but of gender complementarity, with gender roles being separate but equal.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Among the nobles, marriage alliances were often used as a political strategy with lesser nobles marrying daughters from more prestigious lineages whose status was then inherited by their children.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Nobles were also often polygamous, with lords having many wives.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Polygamy was not very common among the commoners and some sources describe it as being prohibited.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The main unit of Aztec political organization was the city-state, in Nahuatl called the *altepetl*, meaning "water-mountain".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Each altepetl was led by a ruler, a *tlatoani*, with authority over a group of nobles and a population of commoners.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The altepetl included a capital that served as a religious center, the hub of distribution and organization of a local population that often lived spread out in minor settlements surrounding the capital.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Altepetl was also the main source of ethnic identity for the inhabitants, even though Altepetl was frequently composed of groups speaking different languages.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Each altepetl would see itself as standing in political contrast to other altepetl polities, and war was waged between altepetl states.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In this way, Nahuatl-speaking Aztecs of one Altepetl would be solidary with speakers of other languages belonging to the same altepetl, but enemies of Nahuatl speakers belonging to other competing altepetl states.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In the basin of Mexico, altepetl was composed of subdivisions called *calpolli*, which served as the main organizational unit for commoners.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In Tlaxcala and the Puebla valley, the altepetl was organized into *teccalli* units headed by a lord (Nahuatl languages: *tecutli*), who would hold sway over a territory and distribute rights to land among the commoners.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] A calpolli was at once a territorial unit where commoners organized labor and land use since the land was not private property, and also often a kinship unit as a network of families that were related through intermarriage.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Calpolli leaders might be or become members of the nobility, in which case they could represent their Calpolli interests in the altepetl government.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In the valley of Morelos, archeologist Michael E.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Smith estimates that a typical altepetl had from 10,000 to 15,000 inhabitants, and covered an area between 70 and 100 square kilometers (27 and 39 sq mi).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In the Morelos Valley, altepetl sizes were somewhat smaller.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Smith argues that the altepetl was primarily a political unit, made up of the population with allegiance to a lord, rather than as a territorial unit.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] He makes this distinction because in some areas minor settlements with different altepetl allegiances were interspersed.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Aztec Empire was ruled by indirect means.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Like most European empires, it was ethnically very diverse, but unlike most European empires, it was more of a hegemonic confederacy than a single system of government.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] It was also a discontinuous empire because not all dominated territories were connected; for example, the southern peripheral zones of Xoconochco were not in direct contact with the center.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Such compliance was secured by establishing and maintaining a network of elites, related through intermarriage and different forms of exchange.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Nevertheless, the expansion of the empire was accomplished through military control of frontier zones, in strategic provinces where a much more direct approach to conquest and control was taken.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Such strategic provinces were often exempt from taxation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Aztecs even invested in those areas, by maintaining a permanent military presence, installing puppet rulers, or even moving entire populations from the center to maintain a loyal base of support.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] In this way, the Aztec system of government distinguished between different strategies of control in the outer regions of the empire, far from the core in the Valley of Mexico.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Some provinces were treated as subject provinces, which provided the basis for economic stability for the empire, and strategic provinces, which were the basis for further expansion.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Although the form of government is often referred to as an empire, most areas within the empire were organized as city-states, known as *altepetl* in Nahuatl.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] These were small polities ruled by a hereditary leader (*tlatoani*) from a legitimate noble dynasty.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The Early Aztec period was a time of growth and competition among *altepetl*.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] Even after the confederation of the Triple Alliance was formed in 1427 and began its expansion through conquest, the *altepetl* remained the dominant form of organization at the local level.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p01] The efficient role of the altepetl as a regional political unit was largely responsible for the success of the empire's hegemonic form of control.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Like all Mesoamerican peoples, Aztec society was organized around maize agriculture.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The humid environment in the Valley of Mexico with its many lakes and swamps permitted intensive agriculture.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The main crops in addition to maize were beans, squashes, chilies, and amaranth.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Particularly important for agricultural production in the valley was the construction of chinampas on the lake, artificial islands that allowed the conversion of the shallow waters into highly fertile gardens that could be cultivated year-round.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Chinampas are human-made extensions of agricultural land, created from alternating layers of mud from the bottom of the lake, and plant matter and other vegetation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] These raised beds were separated by narrow canals, which allowed farmers to move between them by canoe.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Chinampas were extremely fertile pieces of land, and yielded, on average, seven crops annually.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Based on current chinampa yields, it has been estimated that one hectare (2.5 acres) of chinampa would feed 20 individuals and 9,000 hectares (22,000 acres) of *chinampas* could feed 180,000.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The Aztecs further intensified agricultural production by constructing systems of artificial irrigation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] While most of the farming occurred outside the densely populated areas, within the cities there was another method of (small-scale) farming.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Each family had a garden plot where they grew maize, fruits, herbs, medicines, and other important plants.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] When the city of Tenochtitlan became a major urban center, water was supplied to the city through aqueducts from springs on the banks of the lake, and they organized a system that collected human waste for use as fertilizer.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Through intensive agriculture, the Aztecs were able to sustain a large urbanized population.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The lake was also a rich source of proteins in the form of aquatic animals such as fish, amphibians, shrimp, insects and insect eggs, and waterfowl.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The presence of such varied sources of protein meant that there was little use for domestic animals for meat (only turkeys and dogs were kept), and scholars have calculated that there was no shortage of protein among the inhabitants of the Valley of Mexico.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The excess supply of food products allowed a significant portion of the Aztec population to dedicate themselves to trades other than food production.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Apart from taking care of domestic food production, women weaved textiles from agave fibers and cotton.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Men also engaged in craft specializations such as the production of ceramics and obsidian and flint tools and of luxury goods such as beadwork, featherwork, and the elaboration of tools and musical instruments.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Sometimes entire calpollis specialized in a single craft, and in some archeological sites large neighborhoods have been found where- only a single craft specialty was practiced.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The Aztecs did not produce much metalwork but did have knowledge of basic smelting technology for gold, and they combined gold with precious stones such as jade and turquoise.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Copper products were generally imported from the Tarascans of Michoacan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Products were distributed through a network of markets; some markets specialized in a single commodity (e.g., the dog market of Acolman), and other general markets with the presence of many different goods.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Markets were highly organized with a system of supervisors taking care that only authorized merchants were permitted to sell their goods, and punishing those who cheated their customers or sold substandard or counterfeit goods.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] A typical town would have a weekly market (every five days), while larger cities held markets every day.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Cortés reported that the central market of Tlatelolco, Tenochtitlan's sister city, was visited by 60,000 people daily.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Some sellers in the markets were petty vendors; farmers might sell some of their produce, potters sold their vessels, and so on.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Other vendors were professional merchants who traveled from market to market seeking profits.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The pochteca were specialized long-distance merchants organized into exclusive guilds.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] They made long expeditions to all parts of Mesoamerica bringing back exotic luxury goods, and they served as the judges and supervisors of the Tlatelolco market.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Although the economy of Aztec Mexico was commercialized (in its use of money, markets, and merchants), land and labor were not generally commodities for sale, though some types of land could be sold between nobles.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] In the commercial sector of the economy, several types of money were in regular use.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Small purchases were made with cacao beans, which had to be imported from lowland areas.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] In Aztec marketplaces, a small rabbit was worth 30 beans, a turkey egg cost three beans, and a tamal cost a single bean.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] For larger purchases, standardized lengths of cotton cloth, called quachtli, were used.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] There were different grades of quachtli, ranging in value from 65 to 300 cacao beans.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] About 20 quachtli could support a commoner for one year in Tenochtitlan.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Another form of distribution of goods was through the payment of taxes.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] When an altepetl was conquered, the victor imposed a yearly tax, usually paid in the form of whichever local product was most valuable or treasured.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Several pages from the Codex Mendoza list subject towns along with the goods they supplied, which included not only luxuries such as feathers, adorned suits, and greenstone beads, but more practical goods such as cloth, firewood, and food.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Taxes were usually paid twice or four times a year at differing times.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Archaeological excavations in the Aztec-ruled provinces show that incorporation into the empire had both costs and benefits for provincial peoples.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] On the positive side, the empire promoted commerce and trade, and exotic goods from obsidian to bronze managed to reach the houses of both commoners and nobles.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Trade partners also included the enemy Purépecha (also known as Tarascans), a source of bronze tools and jewelry.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] On the negative side, imperial taxes imposed a burden on commoner households, who had to increase their work to pay their share of taxes.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Nobles, on the other hand, often made out well under the imperial rule because of the indirect nature of imperial organization.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The empire had to rely on local kings and nobles and offered them privileges for their help in maintaining order and keeping the tax revenue flowing.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Aztec society combined a relatively simple agrarian rural tradition with the development of a truly urbanized society with a complex system of institutions, specializations, and hierarchies.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The capital city of the Aztec empire was Tenochtitlan, now the site of modern-day Mexico City.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Built on a series of islets in Lake Texcoco, the city plan was based on a symmetrical layout that was divided into four city sections called *campan* (directions).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Tenochtitlan was built according to a fixed plan and centered on the ritual precinct, where the Great Pyramid of Tenochtitlan rose 50 meters (160 ft) above the city.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Houses were made of wood and loam, and roofs were made of reed, although pyramids, temples, and palaces were generally made of stone.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The city was interlaced with canals, which were useful for transportation.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Anthropologist Eduardo Noguera estimated the population at 200,000 based on the house count and merging the population of Tlatelolco (once an independent city, but later became a suburb of Tenochtitlan).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] If one includes the surrounding islets and shores surrounding Lake Texcoco, estimates range from 300,000 to 700,000 inhabitants.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Smith gives a somewhat smaller figure of 212,500 inhabitants of Tenochtitlan based on an area of 1,350 hectares (3,300 acres) and a population density of 157 inhabitants per hectare (60/acre).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The second largest city in the valley of Mexico in the Aztec period was Texcoco with some 25,000 inhabitants dispersed over 450 hectares (1,100 acres).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Around the sacred precinct were the royal palaces built by the tlatoanis.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The centerpiece of Tenochtitlan was the Templo Mayor, the Great Temple, a large stepped pyramid with a double staircase leading up to two twin shrines – one dedicated to Tlaloc, the other to Huitzilopochtli.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] This was where most of the human sacrifices were carried out during the ritual festivals and the bodies of sacrificial victims were thrown down the stairs.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The temple was enlarged in several stages, and most of the Aztec rulers made a point of adding a further stage, each with a new dedication and inauguration.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The temple has been excavated in the center of Mexico City and the rich dedicatory offerings are displayed in the Museum of the Templo Mayor.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Archeologist Eduardo Matos Moctezuma, in his essay *Symbolism of the Templo Mayor*, posits that the orientation of the temple is indicative of the totality of the vision the Mexica had of the universe (cosmovision).
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] He states that the "principal center, or navel, where the horizontal and vertical planes intersect, that is, the point from which the heavenly or upper plane and the plane of the Underworld begin and the four directions of the universe originate, is the Templo Mayor of Tenochtitlan".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Matos Moctezuma supports his supposition by claiming that the temple acts as an embodiment of a living myth where "all sacred power is concentrated and where all the levels intersect".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Other major Aztec cities were some of the previous city-state centers around the lake including Tenayuca, Azcapotzalco, Texcoco, Colhuacan, Tlacopan, Chapultepec, Coyoacan, Xochimilco, and Chalco.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] In the Puebla Valley, Cholula was the largest city with the largest pyramid temple in Mesoamerica, while the confederacy of Tlaxcala consisted of four smaller cities.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] In Morelos, Cuahnahuac was a major city of the Nahuatl-speaking Tlahuica tribe, and Tollocan in the Toluca Valley was the capital of the Matlatzinca tribe which included Nahuatl speakers as well as speakers of Otomi and the language today called Matlatzinca.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Most Aztec cities had a similar layout with a central plaza with a major pyramid with two staircases and a double temple oriented toward the west.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Priests and educated upper classes held more monistic views, while the popular religion of the uneducated tended to embrace the polytheistic and mythological aspects.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] In common with many other indigenous Mesoamerican civilizations, the Aztecs put great ritual emphasis on calendrics, and scheduled festivals, government ceremonies, and even war around key transition dates in the Aztec calendar.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Public ritual practices could involve food, storytelling, and dance, as well as ceremonial warfare, the Mesoamerican ballgame, and human sacrifice, as a manner of payment for, or even effecting, the continuation of the days and the cycle of life.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The four main deities worshiped by the Aztecs were Tlaloc, Huitzilopochtli, Quetzalcoatl, and Tezcatlipoca.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Tlaloc is a rain and storm deity; Huitzilopochtli, a solar and martial deity and the tutelary deity of the Mexica tribe; Quetzalcoatl, a wind, sky, and star deity and cultural hero; and Tezcatlipoca, a deity of the night, magic, prophecy, and fate.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The Great Temple in Tenochtitlan had two shrines on its top, one dedicated to Tlaloc, the other to Huitzilopochtli.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The two shrines represented two sacred mountains: the left one was Tonacatepetl, the Hill of Sustenance, whose patron god was Tlaloc, and the right one was Coatepec, whose patron god was Huitzilopochtli.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Quetzalcoatl and Tezcatlipoca each had separate temples within the religious precinct close to the Great Temple, and the high priests of the Great Temple were named "*Quetzalcoatl Tlamacazqueh*".
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] In some regions, particularly Tlaxcala, Mixcoatl or Camaxtli was the main tribal deity.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] A few sources mention a binary deity, Ometeotl, who may have been a god of the duality between life and death, male and female, and who may have incorporated Tonacatecuhtli and Tonacacihuatl.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Some historians argue against the notion that Ometeotl was a dual god, claiming that scholars are applying their preconceived ideas onto translated texts.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Apart from the major deities, there were dozens of minor deities each associated with an element or concept, and as the Aztec empire grew so did their pantheon because they adopted and incorporated the local deities of conquered people into their own.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Additionally, the major gods had many alternative manifestations or aspects, creating small families of gods with related aspects.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Aztec mythology is known from many sources written down in the colonial period.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] One set of myths, called Legend of the Suns, describes the creation of four successive suns, or periods, each ruled by a different deity and inhabited by a different group of beings.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Each period ends in a cataclysmic destruction that sets the stage for the next period to begin.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] In this process, the deities Tezcatlipoca and Quetzalcoatl appear as adversaries, each destroying the creations of the other.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The current Sun, the fifth, was created when a minor deity sacrificed himself on a bonfire and turned into the sun, but the sun only begins to move once the other deities sacrifice themselves and offer it their life force.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] In another myth of how the earth was created, Tezcatlipoca and Quetzalcoatl appear as allies, defeating a giant crocodile Cipactli, and requiring her to become the earth, allowing humans to carve into her flesh and plant their seeds, on the condition that in return they will offer blood to her.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] In the story of the creation of humanity, Quetzalcoatl travels with his twin Xolotl to the underworld and brings back bones which are then ground like corn on a metate by the goddess Cihuacoatl, the resulting dough is given human form and comes to life when Quetzalcoatl imbues it with his blood.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] Huitzilopochtli is the deity tied to the Mexica tribe and he figures in the story of the origin and migrations of the tribe.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] On their journey, Huitzilopochtli, in the form of a deity bundle carried by the Mexica priest, continuously spurs the tribe by pushing them into conflict with their neighbors whenever they are settled in a place.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] In another myth, Huitzilopochtli defeats and dismembers his sister the lunar deity Coyolxauhqui, and her four hundred brothers at the hill of Coatepetl.
[src:chrysler-cordoba/aztec-p02] The southern side of the Great Temple, also called Coatepetl, was a representation of this myth, and at the foot of the stairs lay a large stone monolith carved with a representation of the dismembered goddess.
